-- PartialEq / Eq ‚Äî partial vs. lawful equality (library proposal 004, WI-644).
--
-- PartialEq holds the `eq`/`neq` OPERATIONS: any two-valued comparison, with NO
-- reflexivity law. This is all a body goal `eq(?x, ?y)` needs, and it is what
-- IEEE `Float` provides (`nan eq nan = false`, `-0.0 eq +0.0 = true`).
--
-- Eq `requires PartialEq` and adds ONLY the reflexivity law `eq_refl` ‚Äî a lawful-
-- equivalence marker + obligation, no new operation (`Eq.eq` is the inherited
-- `PartialEq.eq`). `Set`/`Map` keys, dedup, and sort require this lawful Eq.
-- `Float` does NOT provide Eq: it cannot discharge `eq(?a,?a) <=> true` at NaN.
--
-- NB `eq_refl` is a DORMANT, documentation-only obligation: it is not discharged
-- or refuted per instance, and does not fire as a rewrite (the semantic `eq` is
-- builtin-backed). WI-658 (delivered) makes a `provides Eq[Float]` a load error
-- NOT by refuting `eq_refl` at NaN, but via the `NonEq` route below ‚Äî Float
-- provides `NonEq` (witnessed non-reflexivity) and `Eq` ‚ä• `NonEq` is checked at
-- load (`check_eq_noneq_exclusive`). Use-site `requires Eq[K]` enforcement (so
-- `Map[K = Float]` is a load error) is WI-649, still open.
sort anthill.prelude.PartialEq
  import anthill.reflect.{not}

  sort T = ?
  operation {
    eq(a: T, b: T) -> Bool
    neq(a: T, b: T) -> Bool
  }
  rule neq(?a, ?b) <=> not(eq(?a, ?b))
end

-- Eq: lawful (reflexive) equality. The `eq`/`neq` operations are inherited from
-- PartialEq via the requires-chain (WI-614); Eq adds only the law.
sort anthill.prelude.Eq
  sort T = ?
  requires PartialEq[T]

  -- Reflexivity ‚Äî the law a partial carrier (IEEE Float) cannot satisfy. Dormant /
  -- documentation-only (see the file header): NOT discharged per instance. A
  -- `provides Eq[Float]` is blocked instead by the `NonEq` exclusion (WI-658).
  rule eq_refl: eq(?a, ?a) <=> true
end

-- NonEq: a carrier declares its equality is NOT reflexive by exhibiting a
-- WITNESS ‚Äî `nonEqRefl()` returns some value `w` with `eq(w, w) = false`. This
-- is the constructive form of `‚àÉx. eq(x, x) = false` (Anthill has no `‚àÉ` in rule
-- bodies, so the existential is Skolemized to a nullary witness operation). It
-- is what a partial carrier like IEEE `Float` provides INSTEAD of the lawful
-- `Eq`: Float cannot be reflexive (`eq(nan, nan) = false`), and says so by
-- exhibiting `nan`.
--
-- `Eq` and `NonEq` are MUTUALLY EXCLUSIVE: a carrier's `eq` cannot be both
-- reflexive and non-reflexive. A load-time check (WI-658) rejects any carrier
-- that provides BOTH. A carrier that provides NEITHER is unconstrained ‚Äî the
-- check does nothing without a declaration. Composite carriers (entities /
-- named tuples with a NonEq field) should derive NonEq congruently ‚Äî that is a
-- follow-up (the composite Eq/NonEq derivation ticket).
sort anthill.prelude.NonEq
  sort T = ?
  requires PartialEq[T]

  -- A witness value not equal to itself. For a genuine partial carrier
  -- `eq(nonEqRefl(), nonEqRefl()) = false` (Float: `nonEqRefl() = nan`).
  operation nonEqRefl() -> T
end
